-- BHP, Lonmin, Nampak May Move: South Africa Stock Market Preview
-- B y   G a r t h   T h e u n i s s e n
-- 2010-12-13T06:19:09Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-13/bhp-billiton-lonmin-may-move-south-africa-stock-market-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in  South Africa .
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and prices
are from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  fell for a
second day, losing 128.85, or 0.4 percent, to 31,488.81 at the 5
p.m. close in Johannesburg, paring the week’s gain to 0.4
percent.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ): The world’s largest mining
company is in talks with the National Union of Metalworkers to
resolve a wage dispute at the company’s aluminum smelter
following workers’ rejection of an increased offer last week.
The company’s stock fell 83 cents, or 0.3 percent, to 266 rand.  Capital Shopping Centres Group Plc  (CSO SJ): The U.K.’s
biggest shopping-mall owner said yesterday a proposal by Simon
Property Group Inc. of an alternative financing plan for its
purchase of the Trafford Centre mall in Manchester, England, is
impracticable. Capital Shopping fell 9 cents, or 0.2 percent, to
42 rand.  Illovo Sugar Ltd.  (ILV SJ): South Africa’s government
backed a request by farmers for preferential access to European
markets for its sugar exports, Business Day said, citing
Department of Trade and Industry spokesman, Charles Mnisi.
Illovo gained 20 cents, or 0.7 percent, to 27.30 rand.  Tongaat
Hulett Ltd.  rose 70 cents, or 0.7 percent, to 106. 20 rand.  Lonmin Plc  (LON SJ): The world’s third-largest platinum
producer is scheduled to resume talks with the National Union of
Mineworkers to resolve a wage dispute. Stock of the company fell
1.92 rand, or 1 percent, to 199.88 rand.  Nampak Ltd.  (NPK SJ): The packaging company said it will
sell its European cartons and healthcare business to Maximus
Holding II S.a.r.l and use the 65 million pounds ($103 million)
in net proceeds from the deal to reduce debt and invest in other
businesses. Nampak gained 9 cents, or 0.4 percent, to 22.45
rand.  Telkom South Africa Ltd.  (TKG SJ): The acting Chief
Executive Officer of Africa’s largest fixed-line phone company,
Jeffrey Hedberg, hosts an end of year media lunch. The company’s
shares fell 54 cents, or 1.5 percent, to 35.81 rand.  Shares or American depositary receipts of the following
South African companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) added 2.1 percent to $24.12.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) gained 0.9 percent to $48.79. BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) rose 0.2 percent to $78.27. DRDGold Ltd.
(DROOY US) advanced 1.4 percent to $4.96. Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI
US) lost less than 0.1 percent to $17.79. Harmony Gold Mining
Co. (HMY US) fell almost 0.1 percent to $12.36. Impala Platinum
Holdings Co. (IMPUY US) slid 0.6 percent to $31.70. Sappi Ltd.
(SPP US) declined 0.6 percent to $5.02. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) rose
0.4 percent to $48.10. Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TLKGY US)
dropped 2.3 percent to $20.77.  To contact the reporter on this story:
